`crates/steno` is a compiler crate plus its test harness: `.steno` source in, Plover JSON dictionaries / LSP snippets / structured blocks out, exercised end-to-end against a real corpus (`dict.steno`) checked in at the repo root. Depending on this crate means depending on `src/`'s re-exported pipeline functions (`parse` → `expand` → `render`/`snippet`/`blocks`) and their typed errors; the `tests/` tree is not consumed by anything but exists as the executable spec for exact output strings and error text across every stage.

The one fact that spans both subtrees: `dict.steno` is both the crate's implicit fixture and its test corpus. `src/` contains no knowledge of it — the library never reads files — but eight files under `tests/` load it independently by relative path from `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`, hardcoding specific strokes and corpus-wide counts. Any edit to `dict.steno` (renaming a stroke, changing an arity, adding an `@noarg` type) is really an edit to the crate's test suite and must be checked against all eight files, several of which fail via panicking `.unwrap()` rather than descriptive assertions. One such edit already happened — `STKWR-LT` was repurposed — and is patched around identically in `smart.rs` and `snippet.rs` via hand-built `TypedEntry` stand-ins, so any future change to `TypedEntry`/`Entry`/`EntryFlags` layout must update both.

Pipeline order (`parse` → `expand` Pass A → `expand` Pass B → render/snippet/blocks) is architecture in `src/` (stated once, in `lib.rs`) and is re-derived as file dependency order in `tests/` (`parse_source.rs`/`parse_template.rs` → `expand.rs` → `expand_types.rs` → `render.rs`/`smart.rs`/`snippet.rs`/`blocks.rs`). `src/`'s shared subsystems — `stroke/`'s stroke API, `editor/`'s keystroke IR (`PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT` dispatch), `json_out.rs`'s deterministic serializer, `parse/`'s `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr` shape — are each covered from a different angle in `tests/`: `stroke.rs` is round-trip/error spec while `stroke_order.rs` lints the real corpus with the same functions; `editor.rs` tests `interpret`/`Behaviors` synthetically with no corpus dependency; `nvim_plugin.rs` is the only place checking the actual Lua plugin against headless Neovim, also corpus-independent. A new template operator or `Chunk` variant requires coordinated edits across `src/parse/` plus whichever consumer subtree handles it, plus new coverage in the matching `tests/` file.

`bin/` (three binaries) sits outside both trees described above: it depends only on `src/`'s re-exported surface, uses stringly-typed errors instead of `error.rs`'s hierarchy, and each binary independently hardcodes workspace-root resolution that `lib.rs` takes no position on.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence to report.